<F P=100> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Firms in East To Get New Investment Allowance </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Firms in East To Get New Investment Allowance </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1304155794 Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT in German 13 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU1304155794 </F>
<F P=104>  Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["uhl" report: "Eastern Allowance for All Small </F>
Enterprises"] 
  [Text] Bonn, 12 Apr -- The so-called higher investment 
allowance of 20 percent for east German companies of the 
producing industry and the crafts will expire at the end of the 
year, according to a decision made by the coalition's financial 
politicians. At the same time, as early as 1 July 1994 a 
"largely budget-neutral" follow-up regulation is to be 
introduced, which will also include west German and foreign 
companies. According to this new regulation, all small and 
medium-sized companies in the producing industry and crafts get 
a "higher allowance" of 10 percent for investment in the new 
laender. However, they must not employ more than 250 people. 
The subsidized investment volume is being raised to a maximum 
of 10 million German marks [DM] per company and business year. 
For the 20-percent allowance the subsidized investment volume 
is only DM1 million. 

</TEXT>

