Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Sweden </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bjorck: UN Soldiers Detained by Serbs Not Hostages </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bjorck: UN Soldiers Detained by Serbs Not Hostages </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1304172294 Stockholm Radio Sweden in English 1615 GMT 13 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1304172294 </F>
<F P=104>  Stockholm Radio Sweden </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Fifteen UN soldiers from the Nordic peacekeeping 
battalion in Bosnia since Sunday [10 April] have been detained 
by Serbian soldiers at a roadblock northwest of Sarajevo. The 
group, made up of 13 Swedes and two Norwegians, was stopped 
after refusing to hand over explosives that form part of the 
supplies being carried to their colleagues in Tuzla. Sweden's 
Defense Minister Anders Bjorck says he doesn't regard this as a 
hostage situation, adding that the Nordic soldiers will be free 
to leave the area as soon as a relief group arrives on the scene. 
  Sweden is to withdraw the two Air Force transport planes 
that 
have been taking part in relief flights to the Bosnian capital 
Sarajevo when the agreement with the UN High Commissioner for 
Refugees expires next week. This is despite a UN request for 
continued assistance. Military sources in Stockholm cite 
technical reasons, saying the aircraft need overhaul after 
flying two to three times daily to Sarajevo. The planes are the 
only two of Sweden's eight giant Hercules transport planes with 
special protection against heat-seeking missiles and thus 
suitable for the task. Foreign Aid Minister Alf Svensson said 
Sweden is prepared to resume relief flights at a later date. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

