<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Turkish Official Arrives To Discuss CBM's </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Turkish Official Arrives To Discuss CBM's </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1304173994 Nicosia Bayrak Radio in Turkish 1530 GMT 13 Apr 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1304173994 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Bayrak Radio </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tugay Ulucevik, Turkish Foreign Ministry under 
secretary, has said that for mutual trust to be established in 
Cyprus the damage caused to the package of confidence-building 
measures [CBM's] should be rectified and its contents restored 
to its original form. Ulucevik arrived in the Turkish Republic 
of Northern Cyprus [TRNC] this afternoon to assess the latest 
developments on the Cyprus issue. He was received by President 
Rauf Denktas. 
  In a statement prior to the meeting held at the presidency, 
Ulucevik said that it is Turkey's national goal to secure the 
lasting conditions imperative for the tranquil, secure and 
prosperous existence of the Turkish Cypriot community. He noted 
that Turkey shares the view expressed by the UN secretary 
general on November, 1992, that there is a profound confidence 
crisis between the two sides on the island. Ulucevik recalled 
that activities aimed at securing an atmosphere of trust between 
the two sides have been initiated as of May, 1993. He pointed 
out that the Turkish Cypriot side accepted the principles stated 
in the UN secretary general's report dated 1 July, 1993, which 
included the issues of Maras [Varosha] and the Lefkosa [Nicosia] 
International Airport in the belief that the package was going 
to be implemented in full. Ulucevik added that as of 9 March, 
Denktas noted that the package was being distorted and that 
Turkey assessed the package and concurred with Denktas' 
observation. He further recalled the Turkish Foreign Ministry 
announcement concurring with the TRNC observation, adding that 
the aim of his visit to rectify the damage caused to the package 
and restore its contents to its original form. 
  In reply to a question, Ulucevik said that the fact that he 
was visiting the island at the same time as Robert Lamb, U.S. 
State Department's special Cyprus coordinator, was a 
coincidence. Noting that Lamb asked to meet him, Ulucevik added 
that the TRNC is conducting the negotiating process and that 
Turkey is only trying to help advance the talks. He added that 
within this framework it is normal for him to meet with Lamb. 
In reply to another question, Ulucevik said that had the UN 
Security Council not wished to rectify the damage caused to the 
package, the issue would have been closed long ago. He 
concluded by saying that Turkey favors securing an atmosphere of 
trust between the two sides based on the CBM's agreed upon by 
both sides. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-19156 </DOCNO>
