<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Papoulias Letter to UN Rejects Albanian Claims </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Papoulias Letter to UN Rejects Albanian Claims </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1404060194 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 0400 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1404060194 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ambassador Adhamandios Vasilakis, the permanent 
Greek charge d'affaires at the United Nations, conveyed a letter 
from Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias to the UN Security 
Council president. In the letter, the Greek Government rejects 
Albania's unfounded and suspicious claims surrounding the 
incident in Episkopi. The letter stresses that the great haste 
with which Tirana moved to blame the Greek Government is 
unacceptable and that [Albanian President Sali] Berisha's 
government remains negative although Greece has repeatedly asked 
for cooperation to resolve the issue. 
  Papoulias' letter refers to Albania's suspicious intentions 
and motives in taking an unresolved issue and turning it into a 
bilateral dispute. It also accuses the Albanian Government of 
linking the incident with Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic 
of Macedonia--FYROM] and Kosovo. 
  UN diplomatic circles consider Tirana's behavior as a 
desperate effort to disorientate the common view away from the 
serious domestic, economic, political, minority, and human 
rights issues the country is facing. It is believed that the 
Security Council will take no further step but will only suggest 
that the two sides cooperate to resolve the issue. 

</TEXT>

