<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Formally Finalizes Treaties With New Members </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EU Formally Finalizes Treaties With New Members </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1304193994 Paris AFP in English 1914 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1304193994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, April 13 (AFP) -- Treaties to accept 
Austria, Finland, Norway and Sweden into the European Union [EU] 
were formally wrapped up and printed here Wednesday [13 April], 
EU officials said. 
  The treaties took more than a year to negotiate. The final 
major obstacle was removed last month when Britain removed its 
objections to a modification of EU voting rules to take account 
of the EU's first enlargement since 1986. 
  The officials said the treaties were being sent to the 
European Parliament, which must approve them by May 5 if the 
four countries are to have any chance of joining the 12-nation 
union by the target date of January 1 next year. 
  The treaties must also be ratified by the parliaments of EU 
countries, and by popular referendums in all four of the 
applicant countries. 
  Last-minute sticking points, involving particularly fishing 
disputes with Norway and Sweden, were finally overcome late 
Tuesday, the officials said. 

</TEXT>

