<F P=100> France </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paris Not `Policeman of Africa' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Paris Not `Policeman of Africa' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1304175394 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 1700 
GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1304175394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Fighting continues in the Rwandan capital, 
Kigali. [passage omitted] The last French soldier has now left 
the country. Their mission was to protect and to evacuate the 
expatriate community. That mission has now been accomplished. 
As to the ongoing situation, Cooperation Minister Michel 
Roussin this afternoon told parliament that France has no 
intention of acting as the policeman of Africa: 
  [Begin Roussin recording] France has not ceased to try to 
mobilize public opinion in Africa and across the world. We did 
not sit back with our arms folded. Though we realize that the 
2,500 blue berets urgently needed the reinforcement of the 500 
paratroopers to ensure the evacuation of more than 1,500 people, 
let me tell you that the prime minister today asked the foreign 
minister to remind the United Nations of its role. We cannot be 
the policeman of Africa. The international community has a duty 
to take over from us, and the United Nations must now bring the 
different parties together, and bring the protagonists to a 
cease-fire. If France is again called upon, France will answer 
yes. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

