<F P=100> France </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Indicates Drop in Balladur's Popularity </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Indicates Drop in Balladur's Popularity </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1304132394 Paris AFP in English 1124 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1304132394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, April 13 (AFP) -- French Prime Minister 
Edouard Balladur dropped nine points in a month to 44 percent in 
a popularity poll to be published here on Thursday [14 April]. 
  In the poll by the BVA institute for the weekly PARIS-MATCH, 
socialist President Francois Mitterrand shed a point, but at 46 
percent was two points ahead of his conservative prime minister. 
  It was the third time in recent polls that Mitterrand has 
been more popular than Balladur. A CSA institute poll for the 
Catholic weekly LA VIE at the end of March gave 45 percent to 
the president and 40 percent to the prime minister. Figures in a 
Gallup poll at the beginning of April for the weekly EXPRESS 
were 48 and 42 percent. 
  The poll also said there was a five-point increase to 68 
percent in the numbers dissatisfied with the way France is being 
governed, compared with 25 percent satisfied, a six-point fall. 
  On the left, Olympique Marseille chairman Bernard Tapie, who 
faces embezzlement and bribery charges, was up six points to 33 
percent, ahead of opposition Socialist Party leader Michel 
Rocard, who gained a point to 27 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

