<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-072 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> France </F>
<H3> <TI>   No-Confidence Motion in Government Defeated </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    No-Confidence Motion in Government Defeated </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1304201294 Paris France-2 Television Network in French 
1800 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1304201294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-2 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In the National Assembly this afternoon the 
Socialist and Communist deputies tabled a no-confidence motion 
that had no chance of being adopted, and was furthermore, 
rejected a few seconds ago, as it received only 87 votes, and it 
would take 289 to bring the government down. 
  However, it was a good opportunity nevertheless, to 
criticize 
the social policy of the government of Edouard Balladur, and, as 
the Socialist Martin Malvy said, to compare the promises made 
with the results obtained. Communist Alain Bocquet for his part 
advocated the abrogation of the five-year law on employment. 
The prime minister replied during the afternoon: This 
no-confidence motion was tabled by the very same people who are 
responsible for the situation that we inherited. 

</TEXT>

