<F P=101> Belgium </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dehaene on Rwandan Accusations Against UN Troops </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dehaene on Rwandan Accusations Against UN Troops </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1304120194 Brussels BELGA Database in French 1824 GMT 12 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1304120194 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels BELGA Database </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed MAR: "Rwandan Crisis: Belgian Prime </F>
Minister Dehaene Categorically Denies Rwandan Accusations"] 
  [Text] Brussels, 12 Apr (BELGA) -- Belgian Prime Minister 
Jean-Luc Dehaene on Tuesday evening [12 April] categorically 
denied on RTBF [French-language Belgian Radio and Television] 
news the accusations leveled by the Rwandan Foreign and 
Cooperation Ministry, which questioned the actions of the UN 
troops guarding Kigali airport at the time the plane carrying 
Rwandan President Juvenal Habyarimana was destroyed. 
  In a memo dated 11 April and addressed to the UN mission in 
Rwanda (UNAMIR), the Rwandan Ministry questioned the 
"inexplicable failures on the part of the UN troops charged with 
the security of Gregoire Kayibanda airport and its environs, 
failures that made it possible for the criminals to shoot down 
the presidential aircraft." 
  Another part of the memo criticized the "active 
participation 
of certain UNAMIR elements in Rwandan Patriotic Front operations 
against the Rwandan Army." 
  In reply, Mr. Dehaene said: "These accusations are 
completely unfounded. The Belgian UN troops did their job and 
did it correctly." 
  In his reply, Mr. Dehaene also wondered about the 
representativeness of the current, self-proclaimed "government" 
of Rwanda. 
  The prime minister pointed out that the circumstances 
surrounding the death of President Habyarimana would only become 
clear if an investigation were launched by the international 
community. 
  However, without wanting to prejudice the results of the 
inquiry, Mr. Dehaene said: "It does, however, now seem likely 
that the attack came from inside Rwanda." 

</TEXT>

