<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Discusses `Struggle' With Kurd Leader </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kinkel Discusses `Struggle' With Kurd Leader </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1304194094 Hamburg DPA in German 1718 GMT 13 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1304194094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- On Wednesday evening [13 April], 
Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel received the leader of the Iraqi 
Kurds, Jalal Talabani, for talks during which the situation of 
the Kurds in this Arab country and their struggle for autonomy 
were focused on. Talabani, who is the secretary general of the 
"Patriotic Union of Kurdistan" (PUK), which is opposed by 
Baghdad, is currently trying to get more support by traveling 
through severla countries. Since the Gulf War in 1991 Germany 
has provided the Kurds in Iraq mainly with humanitarian aid, 
worth 400 million German marks. 
  German state bodies and private organizations are operating 
a 
common coordination office for German aid in the town of Irbil. 
Recently, German journalist Lissy Schmidt was killed in this 
region; media have cited the Iraqi Government as the one that 
"ordered" the killing. On Tuesday, Talabani confirmed in Bonn 
that his PUK has apprehended two of the suspected killers. 

</TEXT>

