<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Scharping: Keep Foreign Policy Out of Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Scharping: Keep Foreign Policy Out of Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1404092694 Hamburg DPA in German 2315 GMT 13 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1404092694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington (DPA) -- Social Democratic Party of 
Germany [SPD] Chairman Rudolf Scharping has warned the Bonn 
coalition parties, the Christian Democratic Union 
[CDU]/Christian Social Union [CSU] and the Free Democratic Party 
of Germany [FDP], not to drag foreign policy into the election 
campaign. Such attempts to distract from the Federal 
Government's failure in the sphere of domestic policy will not 
be successful, Scharping told journalists on Wednesday night [13 
April] in Washington, where he is currently holding talks with 
U.S. politicians. 
  It is not in Germany's interest to "challenge" longstanding 
traditions in foreign policy "for crude calculations of party 
politics." The SPD's chancellor candidate said it was an 
"astonishing coincidence" that the coalition parties were using 
his absence to schedule two important foreign-policy debates in 
the Bundestag. "This is not necessarily proof of a great degree 
of self-assuredness," Scharping said. 
  At the end of his talks in Washington he rejected the 
impression that his assurance of continuity in German foreign 
policy if the SPD wins the Bundestag election would only mean 
the continuation of the policy of the current Federal Government. 
  It completely underestimated, for example, the importance of 
worldwide problems such as the North-South gap, the population 
explosion, or environmental problems for foreign policy. He 
concurred with his U.S. partners in the talks that these issues 
must be tackled more intensively and with more commitment, 
Scharping said. 
  On Friday, Scharping will travel to New York and meet, among 
others, Jack Smitz, the president of General Motors. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

