<H3> <TI>   Defense Ministry on Evacuation Efforts in Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Ministry on Evacuation Efforts in Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1404085094 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1833 GMT 13 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1404085094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Rwanda: Kigali Airport Under </F>
Italian, Belgian Control"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, April 13 -- The airport in Rwanda's 
war-torn capital Kigali is now under the control of Belgian and 
Italian troops, according to a communique from the Defence 
Ministry. 
  The Italian contingent in the airport consists of 133 men, 
with a further 29 standing by in nearby Nairobi. One Italian 
plane and two Belgian ones are on the apron in the airport. 
  The Italian troops, from the crack Col Moschin battalion, 
have carried out three operations outside the airport precinct 
to bring Italian nationals resident in Rwanda to safety. 
  With the help of the Belgian military, the number of 
Italians 
now evacuated from Rwanda stands at 138, with a further seven 
having reached neighbouring Burundi under their own steam, and 
eight more airlifted from an outlying village by a United 
Nations helicopter. 
  Italy has just under 200 of its nationals in the country, 
most of them nuns and priests. 
  According to the defence ministry, which is keeping a close 
watch on developments in the African country wracked by tribal 
clashes, the situation there is "difficult and dramatic." 

</TEXT>

