<H3> <TI>   Martino: Government To Be Formed `Very Shortly' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Martino: Government To Be Formed `Very Shortly' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1304113294 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 0946 GMT 13 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1304113294 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Martino Says Government Imminent"] </F>
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, April 13 -- Italy's new government will 
be formed "very, very shortly" in the view of Antonio Martino, a 
Friedmanite economist and chief architect of Silvio Berlusconi's 
free-market, tax-cutting economic platform. 
  "I think that the timeframe for the creation of the new 
executive will be very short indeed; the programme is already 
being vetted by the coalition," said the newly elected Forza 
Italia MP on the sidelines of a conference here. 
  Asked about his own immediate future, the man touted by many 
to hold a key economic post in the next government quipped: 
"Those who predict catastrophes suffer twice over, but I'm 
certainly about to give my last university lecture." 
  Before his involvement in politics, Martino was best-known 
as 
a comparatively lone voice in spreading Milton Friedman's 
monetarist theories from his post at a Rome private university, 
Luiss. 
  President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro -- who summoned Berlusconi 
for 
talks this morning -- is expected to give the Forza Italia 
leader a mandate to form an executive after the House speakers 
are elected, on Friday [15 April] or Saturday. 

</TEXT>

