<H3> <TI>   Scalfaro Calls For Reconciliation for Liberation Day </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Scalfaro Calls For Reconciliation for Liberation Day </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1304121694 Milan CORRIERE DELLA SERA in Italian 12 Apr 94 
p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1304121694 </F>
<F P=104>  Milan CORRIERE DELLA SERA </F>
<F P=105>  Italian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Scalfaro: Reconciliation on 25 </F>
April"] 
  [Excerpt] Rome -- Yesterday, in Ciociaria [near Rome], 
remembering a priest who was murdered by the Nazis, Scalfaro 
launched an appeal to "reconcile history with harmony among our 
people." The upcoming 25 April [Liberation Day] must therefore 
become the "day of concord." Fifty years after the Resistance, 
it is high time to bring the second post-war period to a close 
because "what is heard from all the dead, from the dead on all 
sides, from the sufferings of the mothers on all sides, is not 
the voice of divisiveness, resentment, opposition, but the voice 
of unity, fraternity, and love of our fatherland." 
  The appeal also seems to go half way toward meeting 
[National 
Alliance leader] Fini's requests for general pacification in the 
name of all victims, on all fronts, whether on the side of the 
victors or the vanquished. Scalfaro also made an appeal to 
judges: Avoid polemics and avoid being used instrumentally. On 
the other hand, Scalfaro forcefully confirmed the principle of 
the magistrature's autonomy and independence. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

