<H3> <TI>   SPD Says Bonn's Economic Hopes Too Optimistic </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SPD Says Bonn's Economic Hopes Too Optimistic </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1504084094 Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT in German 14 Apr 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> AU1504084094 </F>
<F P=104>  Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["uhl"-initialed report: "Government Too Optimistic"] </F>
  [Text] Bonn, 13 Apr -- In the view of Uwe Jens, economic 
policy spokesman of the Social Democratic Party of Germany 
Bundestag group, the Federal Government is interpreting the 
"meager signs of economic recovery" far too optimistically. 
Even if the GNP were to be about 1 percent higher in 1994 than 
it was in 1993, this does not change anything concerning the 
economic and, above all, the difficult long-term structural 
problems. Therefore, an "active German and European economic 
policy" is necessary. Thus, the Bundesbank should lower the 
prime rate to about 3 to 4 percent by June. The European Union 
must decide quickly on its infrastructure program of about 29 
billion German marks. After the signing of the new GATT 
agreement, the agreed reduction of trade barriers are to be 
implemented quickly. In addition, an innovation offensive 
should be started, Jens said. 

</TEXT>

