<F P=100> BENELUX COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Belgium </F>
<H3> <TI>   Claes on Withdrawal of UN Contingent From Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Claes on Withdrawal of UN Contingent From Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1404162194 Brussels La Une Radio Network in French 1500 
GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1404162194 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels La Une Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Belgian blue helmets in Rwanda are to be pulled 
out. Foreign Minister Willy Claes announced the decision just 
after the religious ceremony that took place this morning in 
honor of the 10 blue helmets killed in Rwanda. Willy Claes: 
  [Begin recording] [Claes] We have decided once and for all 
to 
withdraw Belgian troops from the UN contingent. We have made 
this decision for two reasons: The first is that, on the basis 
of undeniable facts that are confirmed to us every hour by our 
diplomats and our soldiers in Rwanda, this UN peacekeeping 
mission, as defined in tempore non suspecto by the UN Security 
Council, no longer has any sense; moreover, in spite of the 
presence of the UN force, we did not manage to prevent the 
murder of tens of thousands of people. The second reason is 
that, considering the anti-Belgian climate, whatever his 
excellency the Rwandan ambassador in Brussels might say, there 
is such an anti-Belgian climate, that we cannot take the 
responsibility for asking our soldiers to take extra risks. 
  [Correspondent Jean-Michel Moestart] Can one conclude from 
the Belgian decision that if the UN Security Council were to 
give the green light tonight, our blue helmets would leave 
Rwanda at the same time as the Belgian para-commandos deployed 
for the evacuation operation? 
  [Claes] No, we are not making any link between our Belgian 
blue helmets and the Belgian paras. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

