<F P=100> SPAIN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Secretary Urges Improved Workers' Rights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trade Secretary Urges Improved Workers' Rights </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1404124894 Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network in Spanish 1100 GMT 
14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1404124894 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Spain has just made public its position on 
ratification of the GATT world trade liberalization agreement. 
We will now hear from our special correspondent in Marrakech, 
Jose Luis Garcia Sanchez. Good afternoon. 
  [Garcia Sanchez] Hello, good afternoon. The Spanish 
administration is convinced that the signing in Marrakech will 
give a new impulse to world economic growth and to the wellbeing 
of all countries. 
  State Secretary for Trade Apolonio Ruiz Ligero was in charge 
of reading the Spanish position which highlights the need for 
the new world trade body to study the social rights of workers 
in developing countries. 
  Spain believes that forced labor, the lack of trade union 
legislation, and general wages agreements which fail to protect 
third world workers should be condemned. Furthermore, Ruiz 
Ligero says that the signing of the Uruguay Round will favor 
Spain in the long-term, it will not hurt our agriculture, and he 
calls upon Spanish businessmen to test their ability to compete 
in the world marketplace as well as at home. 

</TEXT>

