<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Denktas' Reaction to Kliridhis' Speech Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Denktas' Reaction to Kliridhis' Speech Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1404201694 Nicosia BRTK Television Network in Turkish 1630 
GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1404201694 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia BRTK Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Rauf Denktas has opposed Greek Cypriot 
leader Glavkos Kliridhis' claim that the Cyprus problem can be 
resolved through demilitarization and Cyprus becoming a European 
Union member. He said: We urge Kliridhis to abandon his 
intention to make additions to the package of 
confidence-building measures. 
  In a written statement today, Denktas replied to Glavkos 
Kliridhis' speech in the European Union Parliamentary Assembly. 
Describing the proposal for the demilitarization of Cyprus as a 
deceptive move to undermine the Treaty of Guarantees and 
Turkey's right to obstruct ENOSIS [union of Cyprus and Greece] 
and safeguard the existence of the Turkish Cypriots, Denktas 
said that Kliridhis is ignoring the realities. 
  Stressing that Kliridhis has been disrespectful toward his 
audience and his people by greatly exaggerating the strength of 
the Turkish military forces in Cyprus, Denktas noted: The 
Turkish troops arrived when the final blow was about to be dealt 
on Cyprus by the Greek Cypriot National Guard units under the 
command of Greek officers. They prevented the island from being 
turned into a Greek colony and saved the Turkish Cypriots from 
being destroyed. Denktas recalled that the Cyprus problem was 
created by the Greek Cypriot partner of the Cyprus Republic when 
it destroyed the partnership republic through armed force and 
declared itself the Cyprus Government. He said: The 
prolongation of the Cyprus problem until now is due to the 
world's failure to inform the Greek Cypriot side that it does 
not represent the government of all Cyprus. 
  Criticizing Kliridhis for urging the UN Security Council to 
implement its resolutions on Cyprus, Denktas said: The 
resolutions that refer to the Cyprus Government are not valid. 
They cannot be implemented. A move to implement them will not 
contribute to the establishment of peace in Cyprus. On the 
contrary, it will create an unresolvable chaotic situation in 
the island. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-19274 </DOCNO>
