<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Greek Envoy Meets With UN's Vance on FYROM </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Greek Envoy Meets With UN's Vance on FYROM </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1404195394 Athens ET-1 Television Network in Greek 1800 
GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1404195394 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ET-1 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] UN mediator Cyrus Vance is trying to achieve a 
compromise between Greece and Skopje [The Former Yugoslav 
Republic of Macedonia--FYROM] through goodwill moves. This was 
evident after Vance's meeting with Ambassador Khristos 
Zakharakis, who repeated that the embargo against Skopje will be 
lifted only when Greece's conditions are accepted. 
  [Begin recording] [Correspondent Athanasios Ellis from New 
York] Ambassador Khristos Zakharakis, Foreign Ministry director 
general, and UN mediator Cyrus Vance had a substantive meeting 
just a short while ago. During the meeting, Zakharakis repeated 
Athens' position on lifting the measures against Skopje if 
Greece's three conditions are accepted. Vance, who appears 
determined to achieve an end to the current stalemate, appears 
to be trying to achieve some kind of compromise in the framework 
of which the two sides will proceed simultaneously with goodwill 
moves. As to such moves, diplomatic circles think that Greece 
should lift the economic measures and Skopje should declare its 
intention to abolish the star of Veryina from its flag and 
change the disputed articles in its Constitution. The 
international mediator is also trying to get the positions of 
the two countries to agree on the other point of dispute 
regarding whether the talks should include the issue of the 
name, as Skopje demands, or whether we should remain with the 
confidence-building measures at the current phase, as Athens 
demands. Following the meeting, Zakharakis said that he will 
brief the Greek Government and return on Monday. He also 
stressed that during the meeting with Vance, they discussed all 
the details of the problem. 
  Zakharakis, who met yesterday with U.S. Special Envoy 
Matthew 
Nimetz, also referred to the meeting scheduled between Greek 
Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias and Vance during Prime 
Minister Andreas Papandreou's visit to the United States. 
Consequently, Vance will continue his contacts with the two 
side on Monday. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

