<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kohl Meets Poland's Pawlak, Backs EU Entry </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kohl Meets Poland's Pawlak, Backs EU Entry </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1404135794 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1216 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1404135794 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl has 
promised Poland support from Germany on its path to the European 
Union [EU]. After a meeting with Polish Prime Minister Waldemar 
Pawlak, Kohl told journalists in Bonn today that he will be 
starting initiatives to this effect during Germany's EU 
presidency. Poland's application to join the EU played an 
important part in the talks with Pawlak. 
  Kohl stressed that Poland has made considerable progress in 
its economic reforms over the past few years. Germany wants to 
support that process as far as possible. The chancellor said he 
has always resisted any suggestion that Germany's eastern 
borders could represent the EU's border in the future. It is 
therefore important for Poland, like the Czech Republic, 
Slovakia, and Hungary, to find its way to the EU. However, the 
decision on EU membership rests in the first instance with those 
countries themselves. 
  Kohl stressed that German-Polish relations have developed 
positively over the past years. The task for the future is to 
achieve equally trusting and good-neighborly relations with 
Poland as exist with France. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

