<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Butrus-Ghali: UN Will Not Be Blackmailed in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Butrus-Ghali: UN Will Not Be Blackmailed in Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1504165094 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 1600 
GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1504165094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] The situation remains very tense in Bosnia. 
[passage omitted] Several hundred blue helmets, including many 
French soldiers, are still prisoners of the Bosnian Serbs. The 
French Foreign Ministry has said that it could not accept that 
UNPROFOR [UN Protection Force] should be taken hostage. 
[passage omitted] A moment ago in Madrid, the UN secretary 
general said he would not hesitate to order new air strikes: 
  [Begin Butrus-Ghali recording, in French] We will go through 
to the end concerning the use of air power in former Yugoslavia. 
If we need air support, we will not hesitate to call on NATO to 
use force to protect the United Nations forces. This is a very 
clear warning which I would like to send from here in Madrid to 
those elements in Yugoslavia that are trying to oppose the 
action of the United Nations. The United Nations will not give 
in to any blackmail. The United Nations represents the 
international community and represents the will of the 
international community. If the international community decides 
to use force, the United Nations will decide to use force. In 
any case, the use of force must be decided taking account of the 
situation on the ground. The soldiers that we have on the 
ground advise us how, where, and when force should be used. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

