<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel: EU's Eastward Expansion To Top Germany's Agenda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kinkel: EU's Eastward Expansion To Top Germany's Agenda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1504195994 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1808 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1504195994 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest (DDP/ADN) -- According to German Foreign 
Minister Klaus Kinkel, Germany will continue to be the "patron 
and advocate" of eastward expansion of the European Union (EU). 
Therefore, this issue will top the agenda of the German EU 
Presidency, which starts on 1 July, Kinkel said in Budapest 
today, at a forum organized by the Friedrich Naumann Foundation, 
the Hungarian opposition Alliance of Young Democrats (FiDeSZ), 
and the Alliance of Free Democrats (SZDSZ) on the subject of 
"The Visegrad Countries and the European Union." 
  The successful regional integration of the Visegrad states, 
Poland, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Poland [as received], and 
Hungary was a preliminary stage to EU integration, the German 
foreign minister said. However, great efforts by all sides were 
still necessary before these countries could become members of 
the Union. Kinkel affirmed his proposal of a "Marshal Plan for 
the minds," under which, among other things, thousands of 
students from Central and East Europe should go to the EU states 
and college teaching staff should be exchanged. 
  In the area of security too, integration rather than 
exclusion was necessary. The correct way to achieve this was, 
for instance, the "evolutionary concept" of a Partnership for 
Peace, Kinkel said. In addition, association with the WEU 
[Western European Union] needed to be possible in order to bring 
the East European states closer to the European Union. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

