<H3> <TI>   Korean, British Foreign Ministers Discuss Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Korean, British Foreign Ministers Discuss Nuclear Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1604005394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0044 GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1604005394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, April 15 (YONHAP) -- South Korean Foreign 
Minister Han Sung-chu, currently on a European tour, met his 
British counterpart Douglas Hurd in London Friday [15 April] to 
discuss the North Korean nuclear dispute and other issues of 
mutual interest. Hurd invited President Kim Yong-sam to visit 
London during his one-hour talk with Han. 
  Han explained recent developments after the UN Security 
Council issued a statement calling on North Korea to permit 
nuclear inspections, including Kim's summits in Japan and China 
and his own trip to the two countries, the United States and 
Russia, and his meeting with Hans Blix, director-general of the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA). 
  The foreign minister elaborated on Seoul's decisions to 
withdraw its demand for an inter-Korean exchange of envoys as a 
precondition to further high-level Pyongyang-Washington talks 
and to accommodate North Korean loggers fleeing from Siberian 
camps. 
  London expressed "a full understanding" of Seoul's new 
measures as well as hope that the nuclear issue would now be 
resolved. 
  Han thanked Hurd for Britain's support in handling the 
nuclear problem on the international stage, to which Hurd 
responded with a promise of continued cooperation. 
  The British secretary said his government welcomes a visit 
by 
President Kim anytime. 
  Han met British strategy experts later in the evening to 
further discuss the nuclear issue and is scheduled to speak at a 
lunch Saturday sponsored by a non-governmental body, the 
Korea-Britain Forum. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

