<H3> <TI>   Mission in Bosnia `No Issue' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mission in Bosnia `No Issue' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1604202994 Hamburg DPA in German 1414 GMT 16 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1604202994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn -- For Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel (Free 
Democratic Party of Germany), the dispatch of German soldiers to 
territories in the former Yugoslavia is no issue. Even if a 
decision by the Constitutional Court should allow the 
participation of the Bundeswehr in armed blue beret missions, as 
it is generally expected to do, German soldiers would not be 
deployed in the former Yugoslavia, Kinkel told DPA today. 
  The participation of Bundeswehr soldiers would have to be 
approved in every individual case by the Bundestag, the foreign 
minister stressed. An approval by the Bundestag for an armed or 
even unarmed German mission in the former Yugoslavia is 
certainly not to be expected. Thus, this problem is not topical. 
  Chancellor Helmut Kohl (Christian Democratic Union) 
expressed 
a similar view at the end of last week. "In this part of 
Europe, the memory of World War II is particularly present. 
Thus, one must ask oneself the question whether German help -- 
no matter what kind -- is welcome at all," the chancellor stated 
in an interview with SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG. The chairman of the 
Bundestag group of the Christian Democratic Union/Christian 
Social Union, Wolfgang Schaeuble, basically advocated 
participation in military operations in Bosnia in an interview 
with the Cologne EXPRESS (Saturday edition). However, this is 
only possible "if all those affected agree." 

</TEXT>

