<H3> <TI>   Hopes for Russian Pressure on Serbs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hopes for Russian Pressure on Serbs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1704173894 Mainz ZDF Television Network in German 1700 GMT 
17 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1704173894 </F>
<F P=104>  Mainz ZDF Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel by Karl Otto </F>
Gerhard in Bonn -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Gerhard] Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel expressed 
the hope that Russia will exert more pressure on the Serbs. 
  [Kinkel] It is very important and decisive now for the 
Russian side to exert massive and urgently needed pressure on 
the Serbs, so that the Serbs give up the stranglehold of Gorazde. 
  [Gerhard] What should the Russians tell the Serbs? 
  [Kinkel] They must tell them that we have achieved major 
progress in the political sphere -- Sarajevo, access to Tuzla, 
the agreement between the Croats and the Muslims, and Mostar. 
It must be possible to extinguish the other fires in a 
mosaic-like manner, which also includes -- in a symbolic manner 
-- Gorazde. 
  [Gerhard] What about the German contribution? Are we only 
observers or can we participate actively in the peace process? 
  [Kinkel] We cannot send German soldiers to the former 
Yugoslavia because of our constitution. We are very committed 
in the humanitarian area. The political process will be 
continued tomorrow by the 12 foreign ministers in Luxembourg. I 
am in constant contact with my U.S. counterpart and my 
colleagues and friends in the European Union. We are 
participating strongly and are trying to help. 

</TEXT>

