<F P=100> SPAIN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Butrus-Ghali Departs; Optimistic on Peace in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Butrus-Ghali Departs; Optimistic on Peace in Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1704135194 Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network in Spanish 1200 GMT 
17 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1704135194 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid RNE-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The UN secretary general, who left Madrid barely 
half an hour ago, has expressed his optimism about finding a 
solution in order to stop the fighting in Gorazde. Hector 
Arenas was able to speak to him just before he boarded his 
aircraft. Good afternoon. 
  [Arenas] Good afternoon. As he was boarding the aircraft, 
which is now taking him back to New York, UN Secretary General 
Butrus-Ghali agreed to the request from Radio 1 of Radio 
Nacional de Espana to make a statement about the situation in 
former Yugoslavia and Gorazde. Before that, the UN secretary 
general expressed his gratitude to the Spanish people and 
government for the warm welcome that, he said, they had given 
him during his visit to Madrid and Barcelona, highlighting 
Spain's participation, with over 1,000 soldiers, in peace 
operations. 
  Regarding the situation in Bosnia, Butrus-Ghali said that in 
the last few hours he has talked with Yasushi Akashi, his 
representative in Yugoslavia, and with NATO Secretary General 
Manfred Woerner, with whom he discussed, he said, what possible 
measures could be taken to bring peace to that region. 
  The UN secretary general said that when he arrives in New 
York he will hold further consultations with his advisers, 
although I can tell you, he said, that, given that I am by 
definition an optimist, I believe that we will be able to find 
peaceful solutions in this dramatic case. 
  Concerning the situation in Rwanda, Butrus-Ghali said that 
he 
had been in touch by telephone with the UN commander in the 
region who told him that the situation remains confused. 

</TEXT>

