<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ahtisaari Announces Decision To Join PFP </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ahtisaari Announces Decision To Join PFP </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1804101794 Paris AFP in English 0945 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1804101794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Helsinki, April 18 (AFP) -- Finland will join NATO's 
Partnership for Peace [PFP] Programme aimed at improving 
military cooperation with the former Soviet bloc, the Finnish 
president said Monday [18 April]. 
  President Martti Ahtisaari's statement came after the 
governmental committee on foreign affairs recommended that 
neutral Finland should be associated with the North Atlantic 
Treaty Organisation programme. 
  Finland will, however, restrict its participation to 
peacekeeping operations, search, rescue and humanitarian 
functions and environmental protection. 
  A government statement stressed Monday that Finland was not 
seeking any new defence solutions by way of the NATO Partnership 
for Peace. 
  The government has not decided when the documents will be 
signed, but foreign ministry sources said that Foreign Minister 
Heikki Haavisto is likely to sign the programme in Brussels 
early next month. 

</TEXT>

