<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Turkish Assembly's Decision Cited </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reaction to Turkish Assembly's Decision Cited </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1504183494 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1500 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1504183494 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Turkish National Assembly's decision [as heard] 
to turn Ayia Sofia into a mosque represents another provocation 
by Turkey. 
  Deputy Foreign Minister Yeoryios Papandreou said that this 
development causes concern. Public Order Minister Stilianos 
Papathemelis described the Turkish decision as an advanced form 
of provocation. New Democracy issued a statement asking for the 
World Council of Churches to convene and for mobilization of all 
Greeks throughout the world to prevent the desecration of Ayia 
Sofia. 
  Commenting on the proposal to turn Ayia Sofia into a mosque, 
Government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos said that, given its 
everyday practices, Turkey needs to prove that it has some kind 
of relation with what is called European civilization. Turkey, 
the spokesman said, has the duty to prove that. 
  Archbishop Serafim of Athens issued a letter to the United 
Nations and all other international and church organizations as 
well as to the leaders of Christian churches regarding the 
threats against the Ecumenical Patriarchate by Islamists. 

</TEXT>

