<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Balladur on Release Efforts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Balladur on Release Efforts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1504191894 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 1700 
GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1504191894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The 11 volunteers of Premiere Urgence are still 
being held by Serb soldiers several days after their arrest. 
Soldiers claim that they found ammunitions in the 
organization's trucks. Thierry Mauricet, the president of the 
organization, is worried; he questioned Edouard Balladur when he 
met him at the Humagora international meeting of those 
participing in humanitarian actions, which is currently taking 
place at the Palais des Congres in Paris. Listen to this 
dialogue between the two men recorded by Pascal Misrai: 
  [Begin recording] [Mauricet] [words indistinct] Premiere 
Urgence. I am in charge of the issue, and I know that France is 
exerting pressure to obtain their release, but has not been 
successful yet. 
  [Balladur] Yes, for the time being. We have received 
assurances that their lives are not threatened, but we cannot be 
satisfied with this. France is the most active country in 
Yugoslavia, and I believe we cannot ask less than respect for 
those ensuring humanitarian aid. This is the minimum we are 
demanding. 
  [Mauricet] The current hardening of Serb behavior, the 
latest 
detentions of UNPROFOR [UN Protection Force] blue helmets are 
worrying me. What do you intend to do? Is it possible to stop 
the escalation? 
  [Balladur] We hope so, in any case we are attempting to stop 
it by trying to obtain coherent international action by all 
large countries. I thank you for what you are doing. Believe 
me, no one is forgetting the fate of your 11 friends. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

