<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Says Military Unable To Join UN Forces Yet </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kinkel Says Military Unable To Join UN Forces Yet </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1704085294 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0437 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1704085294 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Frankfurt/Main (DDP/ADN) -- According to Foreign 
Minister Klaus Kinkel, Germany cannot at present promise 
Bundeswehr participation in a permanent UN reaction force. He 
holds the view that the wish of UN Secretary General Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali for a reaction force of this kind is "right in 
principle," Kinkel said today on Hessischer Rundfunk radio. At 
the moment it is the case that the United Nations always has to 
go begging when it is a question of getting troops for stemming 
or eliminating crises in troublespots. "We have told 
Butrus-Ghali that we support him on this matter in principle, 
but cannot participate at the moment," Kinkel stressed. He said 
he assumes that the Federal Constitutional Court will reach a 
decision in May or June. 
  It is a question of the Bundestag's being able to decide on 
each individual case for blue helmet or peacemaking measures, 
Kinkel said. However, he added that he adheres to his view that 
the culture of restraint shown by Germany in foreign and 
security policy since the World War II must be "retained at all 
costs." Thus Germany will "in the future say `no' far more 
often than `yes'" even after a decision has been made by the 
Federal Constitutional Court. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

