<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Juppe Calls For Four-Way Talks on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Juppe Calls For Four-Way Talks on Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1804103594 Paris AFP in English 1007 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1804103594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, April 18 (AFP) -- French Foreign Minister 
Alain Juppe on Monday [18 April] called for talks between the 
United States, Russia, the European Union and the United Nations 
to reach a common position on Bosnia. 
  Juppe urged that a study group be set up by the four in 
Geneva in the next few days. 
  The French minister said the Moslem enclave of Gorazde, 
which 
was declared a safe haven by the United Nations, was now under 
Serbian control. His statement came as the town was under 
renewed heavy Serb shelling after tanks rolled into the enclave 
on Sunday. 
  Juppe added that France favoured "neither abandonment nor 
escalation." 
  He said the Geneva study group proposal aimed at defining a 
common approach to apply pressure jointly to relaunch peace 
negotiations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

