<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhirinovskiy Accuses Strasbourg Deputies of Theft </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zhirinovskiy Accuses Strasbourg Deputies of Theft </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1404144894 Paris AFP in English 1438 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1404144894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Strasbourg, April 14 (AFP) - Russian 
ultra-nationalist leader Vladimir Zhirinovskiy left for home on 
Thursday [14 April] complaining European parliamentarians had 
stolen his cap. 
  The navy blue seaman's cap, Zhirinovskiy's trademark, 
disappeared Wednesday night at a reception in the Council of 
Europe restaurant in honour of the assembly's new secretary 
general, Sweden's Daniel Tarschys. 
  In a communique, the Russian MP denounced "the moral level 
of 
European parliamentarians," but advised the thief to wait before 
selling the cap. 
  "The stock exchange quotation of my headgear will increase 
considerably in the near future," the communique said. 
  Zhirinovskiy also renewed his attacks against France "where 
there is no democracy," and against the Council of Europe, 
saying he would do his utmost to prevent the admission of Russia. 
  The Russian MP criticised the French for giving him a 
restricted visa limited to the city of Strasbourg and to the 
duration of the council's parliamentary spring session, and said 
he had no intention of coming back. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

