<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Netherlands UN Observer Disappears in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Netherlands UN Observer Disappears in Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1404145894 Amsterdam DE VOLKSKRANT in Dutch 13 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> BR1404145894 </F>
<F P=104>  Amsterdam DE VOLKSKRANT </F>
<F P=105>  Dutch </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Netherlands UN Observer Missing in </F>
Bosnia"] 
  [Text] A Netherlands military UN observer who was stationed 
in the Muslim enclave of Zepa in eastern Bosnia has been missing 
since around 0007 GMT on Monday [11 April]. The soldier 
concerned is Air Force Major Van Baal. 
  Although all UN observers were supposed to stay inside due 
to 
possible revenge attacks by Bosnian Serbs after the NATO air 
strikes at Gorazde, Van Baal still went out on Monday morning. 
It is not clear why the major did not obey the instruction. 
Also it is not known why he set out with only two interpreters 
and not with one or more UN observers, as customary. 
  Defense Ministry spokesman in The Hague, Colonel F. Olivier, 
said [the Ministry] was "terribly concerned" about Van Baal's 
disappearance. Olivier said that he had only sketchy 
information. 
  The matter was being taken up at a high level in the United 
Nations, Olivier said. The highest civilian UN representative 
in the former Yugoslavia, Yasushi Akashi, was reported to have 
brought up Van Baal's disappearance yesterday during his talks 
in the Serbian stronghold of Pale. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

