Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Schaeuble Views Bundeswehr Involvement in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Schaeuble Views Bundeswehr Involvement in Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1804153794 Berlin DIE WELT in German 16-17 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU1804153794 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Welt-Nachrichtendienst" report: "Bundeswehr to Bosnia: </F>
Schaeuble Contradicts Kohl"] 
  [Excerpt] Bonn -- Differences over the participation of 
Bundeswehr soldiers in missions in the former Yugoslavia seem to 
have appeared between Federal Chancellor Helmut Kohl, of the 
Christian Democratic Union [CDU], and Wolfgang Schaeuble, 
chairman of the CSU/Christian Social Union [CSU] Bundestag Group. 
  Kohl stated yesterday that he was taking an "extremely 
skeptical" position on this issue. Memories of World War II are 
particularly vivid in that part of Europe, which is why we "will 
have to discuss the question of help quietly." The chancellor 
spoke in favor of humanitarian and technical support for the 
reconstruction of Bosnia. 
  Schaeuble, however, did not expressly rule out the 
involvement of German soldiers: "Basically one must say that 
Germany must make its contribution -- including in the military 
sphere -- to peace in the former Yugoslavia. Should peace be 
concluded, then the participation of German soldiers should not 
be ruled out on principle to secure and consolidate peace -- 
under one condition: All parties involved must agree to it." 
  Government Spokesman Vogel said in this connection that he 
saw fundamentally "no differences" between the two leading CDU 
officials on the issue of international Bundeswehr missions. 
Both were basically in favor of such Bundeswehr missions, he 
said, without making any specific mention of Yugoslavia. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

